      <div class="ba-col before" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
        <div class="ba-head">
          <span class="ba-label">#10 · $49–$399/MO · EDITORIAL OPS AND SEO PIPELINE</span>
          <h3 class="ba-title">Letterdrop — Best content ops platform for teams with a managing editor</h3>
          <p class="ba-sub">For content teams that have a head of content in the loop and want keyword research, AI writing, SEO optimization, and publishing in one workflow.</p>
        </div>
        <p style="color: var(--text-2); margin: 0 0 20px;">Letterdrop handles 5 of 6 content pipeline steps — keyword research, briefing, AI writing, optimization, and publishing — leaving only editorial approval to a human. The LinkedIn newsletter integration is strong. The SEO brief quality is one of the best in the category. For small teams with a content strategist who needs to approve everything, Letterdrop tightens the production loop significantly.</p>
        <ul class="ba-list">
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>5 of 6 pipeline steps in one tool</h4><p>The most complete editorial workflow tool outside of theStacc. Keyword research, briefing, writing, optimization, and publishing — only editorial approval stays human.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>Strong LinkedIn newsletter and blog publishing integration</h4><p>Repurposes blog content into LinkedIn newsletters automatically. Useful for B2B teams where LinkedIn is a significant distribution channel.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✓</span><div><h4>High-quality SEO briefs with competitor analysis</h4><p>Briefs include target word count, recommended headings, NLP terms, and competitor gap analysis. Writers produce better first drafts with better starting points.</p></div></li>
          <li><span class="ba-num">✗</span><div><h4>Honest con: requires an editor in the loop</h4><p>Letterdrop accelerates the workflow — it doesn't replace the humans. You still need a managing editor to approve content before it publishes. For teams without that role, the tool adds process without removing the headcount constraint.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

